The paper discusses a framework for an agent learning interactively from a human teacher, which involves modeling the human teacher as a distinct agent and incorporating their signals as observed random variables. This suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG) sub-categories. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of a principled action selection mechanism and belief update mechanism, which are common topics in robotics (cs.RO) and control systems (cs.SY). Finally, the paper emphasizes the potential for complex beneficial interactions, which suggests a focus on human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
